Project Summary: Adaptive Differentiation Resource
1. Purpose

Differentiation in the classroom is one of the most persistent challenges for teachers. Students present with diverse knowledge levels, literacy skills, and learning profiles, but curriculum resources are typically locked into year-level textbooks or rigid online modules.

This project proposes an adaptive, curriculum-aligned digital resource that works alongside classroom teaching to:

Provide every student with access to concepts at their level of knowledge and literacy,

Track multidimensional progress over time,

Reduce teacher workload in designing multiple differentiated tasks, and

Build portfolios of authentic growth across Years 5–6 → Years 7–10 (Victorian Curriculum) → VCE → first-year university level.

2. Scope

Curriculum alignment: Victorian Curriculum (Science, Maths, English, Humanities, Arts, Technologies, etc.)

Senior secondary extension: VCE subjects (e.g., Physics, Chemistry, Environmental Science, English, History).

Tertiary bridging: Introductory content aligned with first-year university expectations (scientific method, academic writing, data analysis).

Entry point: Year 5–6, when literacy gaps begin to strongly influence access to disciplinary content.

3. Core Architecture
3.1 Knowledge Pathways

Diagnostic screening assigns a knowledge level within each subject strand (e.g., rocks and minerals in Science; persuasive writing in English).

Levels scale from Year 5 → Uni-entry, ensuring progression is continuous.

Horizontal enrichment ensures students deepen learning at a level before moving up.

3.2 Literacy Scaffolding

Each knowledge point is expressed in five literacy registers (A–E):

A: Everyday, highly accessible.

B: Scaffolded, semi-technical.

C: Standard curriculum language.

D: Technical disciplinary register (VCE-ready).

E: Advanced academic/professional.

This decouples literacy ability from conceptual understanding.

3.3 Assessment Types

Closed tasks: MCQs, cloze, drag-drop, classification.

Open tasks: Short explanations, data interpretation, justifications.

Inquiry tasks: Simulations, experiments (virtual), case studies.

Communication tasks: Reports, multimodal outputs (text, oral, visual, TTS/STT).

Peer tasks: Peer review with structured rubrics; AI checks flag misuse.

AI use: strictly formative — hints, feedback, adaptive practice; never summative grading.

3.4 Multimodal Access

Input/output supported via text, images, TTS (text-to-speech), STT (speech-to-text).

Multilingual support to address EAL students.

OS disability tools (screen readers, captions, dictation) fully integrated.

4. Differentiation Dimensions

Progress is tracked explicitly across six metrics:

Knowledge progression: from Year 5 curriculum → VCE → first-year uni.

Literacy scaffolding: A–E registers.

Cognitive demand: Bloom’s taxonomy (recall → synthesis).

Response quality: SOLO taxonomy (unistructural → extended abstract).

Horizontal enrichment: breadth/depth at current level before progression.

Communication mode: ability to operate across text, oral, visual, and multimodal forms.

5. Feedback & Reflection

Formative feedback loops embedded at all levels.

Feedforward prompts: “You identified what happened — now explain why.”

Metacognition: self-rating, journals, goal-setting.

Teacher dashboards: diagnostic visualisations of misconceptions, literacy growth, SOLO depth.

Parent dashboards: simplified, multilingual summaries showing growth and next steps.

6. Collaboration & Transfer

Peer assessment and collaboration are embedded, with scaffolds ensuring constructive engagement.

Cross-disciplinary transfer designed in:

Within subject: chemistry ↔ geology in Science.

Across subjects: data skills (Maths) ↔ graphs in Science; persuasive writing (English) ↔ debates in Humanities.

7. Portfolios & Longitudinal Tracking

Each student builds a digital portfolio, with evidence collected over years.

Portfolio includes: closed responses, open inquiry, communication tasks, peer feedback, reflections.

Growth visible from Year 5 → Year 10 → VCE → tertiary.

Exportable for reporting, transitions, or tertiary pathways.

8. Roles & Access

Student: sees personal content, assessments, portfolio, and progress vs. expected benchmarks.

Teacher: full class dashboard, editable tasks, override of AI flags, detailed feedback tools.

Parent/Guardian: read-only simplified dashboard, growth trends, feedforward advice.

School Leader: aggregated analytics (year, subject, cohort).

System safeguards:

SSO authentication, MFA for staff/parents.

RBAC (role-based access control).

Encrypted storage (AES-256) and transit (TLS 1.3).

Privacy compliance: Australian Privacy Principles (APPs), Vic DET requirements.

9. Teacher Role

Teachers remain central:

Interpreting dashboards.

Mediating inquiry and ethical debates.

Providing relational, personalised feedback.

Using system data to plan differentiated classroom activities.

The platform reduces planning burden by offering ready-to-use differentiated resources, but does not displace classroom interaction.

10. Summary

This project proposes a differentiation companion platform for schools:

Curriculum-aligned: Victorian Curriculum (Years 5–10), VCE, and bridging into tertiary.

Adaptive: knowledge and literacy pathways for each learner.

Comprehensive: assessments spanning Bloom’s + SOLO, multiple modalities, peer tasks.

Explicit progress: six dimensions tracked, with portfolios as evidence.

Inclusive: multimodal access, multilingual support, disability integration.

Governed: strong data privacy, clear role access, teacher-in-the-loop design.

It is a scalable, equitable approach to differentiation — supporting teachers, empowering students, and informing parents and schools with clear, authentic evidence of learning growth.

