Project Summary: Adaptive Differentiation Resource
1. Purpose

Differentiating for a diverse classroom is one of the hardest demands on teachers. This project proposes a curriculum-aligned, adaptive digital resource designed to work alongside teaching, not to replace it.

The system provides students with adaptive entry points into curriculum content and assessment, while teachers retain full responsibility for lesson design, classroom activities, and pedagogy. The resource functions as a scaffold and diagnostic aid, easing differentiation and tracking growth, while reinforcing — not replacing — classroom teaching.

2. Scope

Curriculum coverage: Victorian Curriculum (Years 5–10), VCE subjects, and bridging into first-year university.

Entry point: Year 5–6, where literacy differences begin to strongly affect access to disciplinary content.

Cross-subject application: Science, Maths, English, Humanities, Arts, Technologies.

Classroom role: an adjunct resource for differentiation, enrichment, and assessment — not a substitute for classroom lessons, practical activities, or teacher planning.

3. Core Architecture

Knowledge Pathways

Students placed on a level appropriate to their curriculum knowledge (Y5 → Uni-entry).

Includes horizontal enrichment (breadth before depth).

Literacy Scaffolding

Every knowledge concept expressed in five literacy registers (A–E).

Supports both EAL learners and advanced academic learners without conflating literacy with conceptual knowledge.

Assessment Mix

Closed: MCQs, cloze, drag-drop.

Open: explanations, justifications, data interpretation.

Inquiry: simulations, case studies.

Communication: reports, oral responses (STT), multimodal outputs.

Peer: structured collaboration and peer feedback.

AI: strictly formative (misconception flagging, hints, adaptive practice), never summative grading.

Multimodal Access

Input/output via text, images, TTS, STT.

Multilingual and disability support built-in.

4. Differentiation Dimensions (6D Metrics)

Progress is tracked explicitly across six dimensions:

Knowledge progression (Y5 → Uni).

Literacy scaffolding (A–E).

Cognitive demand (Bloom’s).

Response quality (SOLO).

Horizontal enrichment.

Communication mode (text, oral, visual, multimodal).

5. Feedback & Reflection

Embedded formative feedback loops and feedforward prompts.

Self-assessment and reflection tools for metacognition.

Teacher dashboards: diagnostic data for planning differentiated lessons.

Parent dashboards: simplified growth views.

School dashboards: aggregated, non-identifiable data for curriculum monitoring.

6. Collaboration & Transfer

Peer assessment and collaboration embedded at all stages.

Cross-disciplinary transfer encouraged (e.g., maths ↔ science graphs, English ↔ history arguments).

Teacher remains mediator; system supports but never substitutes for human judgment.

7. Portfolios & Longitudinal Tracking

Students build digital portfolios that capture progress across years (Y5–VCE).

Evidence spans closed assessments, inquiry work, peer feedback, multimodal communication, reflections.

Portfolios support reporting, transitions, and pathways into tertiary study.

8. Access & Governance

Role-based access: student, teacher, parent, school leader.

Privacy compliant: APPs, DET guidelines, encrypted storage and transfer.

Parent access: read-only, simplified dashboards.

Teacher role: always in the loop, always responsible for assessment decisions.

9. Teacher Role (Explicit)

Teachers remain responsible for lesson plans, activities, and classroom programs.

The platform serves as:

A diagnostic tool (identifying gaps/misconceptions).

A practice and extension resource for students.

An evidence generator (portfolios, progress tracking).

Teachers mediate feedback, contextualise learning, and integrate outputs into broader curriculum design.

10. Summary

The Adaptive Differentiation Resource is a classroom adjunct, not a replacement for teachers or curriculum. It:

Provides scaffolded access to curriculum content (Y5–VCE–Uni).

Tracks multidimensional progress across six differentiation metrics.

Embeds feedback, peer collaboration, and reflection.

Builds longitudinal portfolios of authentic growth.

Keeps teachers central, reducing their burden while preserving their authority.

It is a scalable, equitable support system for differentiation — complementing classroom teaching, enhancing inclusivity, and ensuring every student has a personalised pathway into learning.